Evidence of the adverse health effects of noise and air pollution is well
 documented.
 Chronic traffic noise exposure in urban environments can cause severe sleep
 disturbance, hearing impairment, tinnitus (3% of all cases), and raised
 stress levels leading to high blood pressure, coronary heart disease, strokes,
 and possibly immune system and birth defects 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "passchier-vermeer:2000"

\end_inset

.
 Air pollution also has a wide variety of adverse health effects, which
 are summarised in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Health-effects"

\end_inset

.
 Groups particularly susceptible to the health effects of air pollution
 include those with respiratory or cardiac diseases or asthma, infants,
 children and the elderly, and those with low socio-economic status (SES),
 low levels of education, poor nutrition and poor general health 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "utell:2005"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is also evidence that individuals' perceptions of air pollution are
 positively related to objective pollution measures, as well as to broader
 evaluations of their local environment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "day:2007"

\end_inset

.
 Individuals are generally aware of the sources of pollution (principally,
 main roads), of its fluctuation according to weather conditions, and of
 the negative health effects with which it is associated, especially for
 children 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bickerstaff:2001"

\end_inset

.
 This makes individuals' perceptions of pollution another plausible route
 by which air pollution may influence LS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
