.
 They have also compared individuals' SWB reports or medical records with
 the proximity of their homes to natural environments, or with alternative
 indicators of local environmental quality 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "vries:2003,kaplan:2001,brereton:2007,rehdanz:2007,maas:2009"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experimental and quasi-experimental studies have investigated physiological
 and psychological effects of exposure to images of different environment
 types 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "berto:2005,white:2010"

\end_inset

 or to short-term interventions bringing subjects into contact with nature
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "ryan:2010,hartig:2003,barton:2010"

\end_inset

.
 They have also related health outcomes or frequency of healthcare-seeking
 behaviour to views of nature in controlled institutional settings 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ulrich:1984,moore:1981"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most such studies report beneficial impacts of natural environments on health
 or wellbeing, but they have some common weaknesses.
 Observational studies measure domestic proximity to natural environments
 but not actual experiences of such environments (which may not occur near
 home, and may occur elsewhere); cannot provide data on the moment-by-moment
 hedonic or affective element of wellbeing; and are reliant on retrospective
 assessments that are subject to substantial recall bias 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "robinson:2002"

\end_inset

.
 Experimental studies are stronger in these respects but, by their nature,
 tell us a limited amount about peoples' real experiences of natural environment
s in their everyday lives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Longitudinal study designs in which participants provide ongoing reports
 of their everyday experience --- Ecological Momentary Assessment (EMA)
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "shiffman:2008"

\end_inset

, the Experience Sampling Method (ESM) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hektner:2007"

\end_inset

, and the Day Reconstruction Method (DRM) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kahneman:2004a"

\end_inset

 --- provide some of the best evidence regarding influences on wellbeing
 in general.
 However, these methods have conventionally been cumbersome, expensive,
 and limited to very small samples 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "killingsworth:2010"

\end_inset

.
 For this reason, and because they have not provided objective location
 data, these ongoing assessment methods have not previously been applicable
 to the study of wellbeing in different environments.
\end_layout

