\begin_layout Subsection
Methodological limitations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Welsch's studies, treating LS as cardinal, compare mean LS and mean air
 pollutant values at the whole-country level.
 The 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "welsch:2002"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "welsch:2007"

\end_inset

 papers conduct a simple cross-sectional analysis of 54 countries.
 This has the advantage that the unobserved heterogeneity across individuals,
 especially with respect to personality traits, may be expected to even
 out 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "welsch:2006"

\end_inset

.
 The disadvantages, however, are that LS and pollution levels are assessed
 only on the most grossly aggregated scale, with no indication of variability
 or of genuine pollution exposures, and that unobserved heterogeneity between
 
\emph on
countries
\emph default
 must then be controlled for.
 Welsch attempts to control for heterogeneity between 54 countries using
 only per capita income, 'rationality' (the number of scientists and engineers
 per thousand people) and---in the 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "welsch:2002"

\end_inset

 but not the 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "welsch:2007"

\end_inset

 paper---'freedom' (as assessed on a 1--7 scale by an American NGO).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
